<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-200-722  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 200 722.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 17 1989 v8 n8 p22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Washington users join BBS system. (Bulletin Board Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Capital PC User GroupComputer Bulletin BoardsUser Groups.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Washington Users Join BBS SystemandM;The Washington, D.C.-area Capital PC User Group (CPCUG) is one of about 90participants in a new nationwide electronic bulletin board created toencourage information exchange among PC user groups.andM;The bulletin board is meant for individuals whose groups are members of theAssociation of PC User Groups (APCUG).andM;Jerry Schneider, former president of CPCUG, is executive director of the neworganization, which has many federal employees as members.andM;The bulletin board is sponsored by Borland International Inc., Intel Corp.'sPersonal Computer Enhancement Operation, the Tymnet division of McDonnellDouglas Corp. and Dell Computer Corp., Austin, Texas.andM;It has three sections -- one providing online conferences and electronic mailto representatives of APCUG member groups, one limited to user group officersand the third made up of forums hosted by the sponsoring corporations.andM;The board is located at Borland in Scotts Valley, Calif.andP;  The phone number is408-439-9367.andO;</TEXT></DOC>